# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gravitation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Although the term *escape velocity* is common, it is more accurately described as a speed than as a velocity because it is independent of direction.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Because gravitational force between two objects depends on their combined mass, the escape speed also depends on mass.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For artificial satellites and small natural objects, the mass of the object makes a negligible contribution to the combined mass, and so is often ignored.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Escape speed varies with distance from the center of the primary body, as does the velocity of an object traveling under the gravitational influence of the primary.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] If an object is in a circular or elliptical orbit, its speed is always less than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] In contrast if it is on a hyperbolic trajectory its speed will always be higher than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] (It will slow down as it gets to greater distance, but does so asymptotically approaching a positive speed.) An object on a parabolic trajectory will always be traveling exactly the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] It has precisely balanced positive kinetic energy and negative gravitational potential energy; it will always be slowing down, asymptotically approaching zero speed, but never quite stop.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Escape velocity calculations are typically used to determine whether an object will remain in the gravitational sphere of influence of a given body.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For example, in solar system exploration it is useful to know whether a probe will continue to orbit the Earth or escape to a heliocentric orbit.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] It is also useful to know how much a probe will need to slow down in order to be gravitationally captured by its destination body.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Rockets do not have to reach escape velocity in a single maneuver, and objects can also use a gravity assist to siphon kinetic energy away from large bodies.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Precise trajectory calculations require taking into account small forces like atmospheric drag, radiation pressure, and solar wind.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] A rocket under continuous or intermittent thrust (or an object climbing a space elevator) can attain escape at any non-zero speed, but the minimum amount of energy required to do so is always the same.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The value *GM* is called the standard gravitational parameter, or *μ*, and is often known more accurately than either *G* or *M* separately.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] A related quantity is the specific orbital energy which is essentially the sum of the kinetic and potential energy divided by the mass.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] An object has reached escape velocity when the specific orbital energy is greater than or equal to zero.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The existence of escape velocity can be thought of as a consequence of conservation of energy and an energy field of finite depth.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Adding speed (kinetic energy) to an object expands the region of locations it can reach, until, with enough energy, everywhere to infinity becomes accessible.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The formula for escape velocity can be derived from the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For the sake of simplicity, unless stated otherwise, we assume that an object will escape the gravitational field of a uniform spherical planet by moving away from it and that the only significant force acting on the moving object is the planet's gravity.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Imagine that a spaceship of mass *m* is initially at a distance *r* from the center of mass of the planet, whose mass is *M*, and its initial speed is equal to its escape velocity, *v*e.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] At its final state, it will be an infinite distance away from the planet, and its speed will be negligibly small.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The same result is obtained by a relativistic calculation, in which case the variable *r* represents the *radial coordinate* or *reduced circumference* of the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] where *r* is the distance between the center of the body and the point at which escape velocity is being calculated and *g* is the gravitational acceleration at that distance (i.e., the surface gravity).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For a body with a spherically symmetric distribution of mass, the escape velocity *v*e from the surface is proportional to the radius assuming constant density, and proportional to the square root of the average density *ρ*.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] This escape velocity is relative to a non-rotating frame of reference, not relative to the moving surface of the planet or moon, as explained below.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The escape velocity *relative to the surface* of a rotating body depends on direction in which the escaping body travels.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The surface velocity decreases with the cosine of the geographic latitude, so space launch facilities are often located as close to the equator as feasible, e.g. the American Cape Canaveral (latitude 28°28′ N) and the French Guiana Space Centre (latitude 5°14′ N).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For an actual escape orbit, a spacecraft will accelerate steadily out of the atmosphere until it reaches the escape velocity appropriate for its altitude (which will be less than on the surface).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] In many cases, the spacecraft may be first placed in a parking orbit (e.g. a low Earth orbit at 160–2,000 km) and then accelerated to the escape velocity at that altitude, which will be slightly lower (about 11.0 km/s at a low Earth orbit of 200 km).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The required additional change in speed, however, is far less because the spacecraft already has a significant orbital speed (in low Earth orbit speed is approximately 7.8 km/s, or 28,080 km/h).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The escape velocity at a given height is ${\sqrt {2}}$ times the speed in a circular orbit at the same height, (compare this with the velocity equation in circular orbit).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] This corresponds to the fact that the potential energy with respect to infinity of an object in such an orbit is minus two times its kinetic energy, while to escape the sum of potential and kinetic energy needs to be at least zero.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The velocity corresponding to the circular orbit is sometimes called the **first cosmic velocity**, whereas in this context the escape velocity is referred to as the **second cosmic velocity**.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For a body in an elliptical orbit wishing to accelerate to an escape orbit the required speed will vary, and will be greatest at periapsis when the body is closest to the central body.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] However, the orbital speed of the body will also be at its highest at this point, and the change in velocity required will be at its lowest, as explained by the Oberth effect.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Escape velocity can either be measured as relative to the other, central body or relative to center of mass or barycenter of the system of bodies.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Thus for systems of two bodies, the term *escape velocity* can be ambiguous, but it is usually intended to mean the barycentric escape velocity of the less massive body.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Escape velocity usually refers to the escape velocity of zero mass test particles.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] For zero mass test particles we have that the 'relative to the other' and the 'barycentric' escape velocities are the same, namely $v_{\text{e}}={\sqrt {\frac {2GM}{d}}}$ .
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] But when we can't neglect the smaller mass (say *m*) we arrive at slightly different formulas.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Because the system has to obey the law of conservation of momentum we see that both the larger and the smaller mass must be accelerated in the gravitational field.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Relative to the center of mass the velocity of the larger mass (*v*p, for planet) can be expressed in terms of the velocity of the smaller mass (*v*r, for rocket).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] where *x* = *v*/*v*e is the ratio of the original speed *v* to the escape velocity *v*e.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Unlike escape velocity, the direction (vertically up) is important to achieve maximum height.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] If an object attains exactly escape velocity, but is not directed straight away from the planet, then it will follow a curved path or trajectory.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Although this trajectory does not form a closed shape, it can be referred to as an orbit.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The shape of the trajectory will be a parabola whose focus is located at the center of mass of the planet.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] An actual escape requires a course with a trajectory that does not intersect with the planet, or its atmosphere, since this would cause the object to crash.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] When moving away from the source, this path is called an escape orbit.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Escape orbits are known as *C*3 = 0 orbits.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] *C*3 is the characteristic energy, −*GM*/2*a*, where *a* is the semi-major axis length, which is infinite for parabolic trajectories.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] If the body has a velocity greater than escape velocity then its path will form a hyperbolic trajectory and it will have an excess hyperbolic velocity, equivalent to the extra energy the body has.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] A relatively small extra delta-*v* above that needed to accelerate to the escape speed can result in a relatively large speed at infinity.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Some orbital manoeuvres make use of this fact.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] If a body in circular orbit (or at the periapsis of an elliptical orbit) accelerates along its direction of travel to escape velocity, the point of acceleration will form the periapsis of the escape trajectory.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The eventual direction of travel will be at 90 degrees to the direction at the point of acceleration.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] If the body accelerates to beyond escape velocity the eventual direction of travel will be at a smaller angle, and indicated by one of the asymptotes of the hyperbolic trajectory it is now taking.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] This means the timing of the acceleration is critical if the intention is to escape in a particular direction.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] This is valid for elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] In this table, the left-hand half gives the escape velocity from the visible surface of the planet or moon (which may be gaseous, for example Jupiter) relative to its centre (that is, not relative to its moving surface).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] In the right-hand half, *V*e refers to the speed relative to the central body (for example the sun).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] The values in the last column are variable, depending on precisely where in a body’s orbit escape velocity is reached, as the orbits are elliptical, not circular (particularly those of Mercury and Pluto).
[src:gravitation/escape-velocity] Let *G* be the gravitational constant and let *M* be the mass of the earth (or other gravitating body) and *m* be the mass of the escaping body or projectile.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In physics, a **gravitational field** or **gravitational acceleration field** is a vector field used to explain the influences that a body extends into the space around itself.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] A gravitational field is used to explain gravitational phenomena, such as the *gravitational force field* exerted on another massive body.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] It has dimension of acceleration (L/T2) and it is measured in units of newtons per kilogram (N/kg) or, equivalently, in meters per second squared (m/s2).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In its original concept, gravity was a force between point masses.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] Following Isaac Newton, Pierre-Simon Laplace attempted to model gravity as some kind of radiation field or fluid, and since the 19th century, explanations for gravity in classical mechanics have usually been taught in terms of a field model, rather than a point attraction.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] It results from the spatial gradient of the gravitational potential field.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In general relativity, rather than two particles attracting each other, the particles distort spacetime via their mass, and this distortion is what is perceived and measured as a "force".
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In such a model one states that matter moves in certain ways in response to the curvature of spacetime, and that there is either *no gravitational force*, or that gravity is a fictitious force.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] Gravity is distinguished from other forces by its obedience to the equivalence principle.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In classical mechanics, a gravitational field is a physical quantity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] A gravitational field can be defined using Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] Determined in this way, the gravitational field **g** around a single particle of mass *M* is a vector field consisting at every point of a vector pointing directly towards the particle.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The magnitude of the field at every point is calculated by applying the universal law, and represents the force per unit mass on any object at that point in space.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] Because the force field is conservative, there is a scalar potential energy per unit mass, Φ, at each point in space associated with the force fields; this is called gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The negative signs are inserted since the force acts antiparallel to the displacement.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The equivalent field equation in terms of mass density *ρ* of the attracting mass is: $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {g} =-\nabla ^{2}\Phi =-4\pi G\rho$ which contains Gauss's law for gravity, and Poisson's equation for gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] Newton's law implies Gauss's law, but not vice versa; see *Relation between Gauss's and Newton's laws*.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] These classical equations are differential equations of motion for a test particle in the presence of a gravitational field, i.e. setting up and solving these equations allows the motion of a test mass to be determined and described.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The field around multiple particles is simply the vector sum of the fields around each individual particle.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] A test particle in such a field will experience a force that equals the vector sum of the forces that it would experience in these individual fields.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] **R***i* is the position vector of the gravitating particle *i*, and **R** is that of the test particle.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The proper time can be expressed in terms of the metric tensor: $d\tau ^{2}=-g_{\mu \nu }dx^{\mu }dx^{\nu }.$ The field that determines the gravitational force is the Christoffel symbols and its derivatives, the metric tensor plays the role of the gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In general relativity, the gravitational field is determined by solving the Einstein field equations $\mathbf {G} =\kappa \mathbf {T} ,$ where **T** is the stress–energy tensor, **G** is the Einstein tensor, and *κ* is the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The latter is defined as *κ* = 8*πG*/*c*4, where *G* is the Newtonian constant of gravitation and *c* is the speed of light.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] These equations are dependent on the distribution of matter, stress and momentum in a region of space, unlike Newtonian gravity, which is depends on only the distribution of matter.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] The fields themselves in general relativity represent the curvature of spacetime.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] General relativity states that being in a region of curved space is equivalent to accelerating up the gradient of the field.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] By Newton's second law, this will cause an object to experience a fictitious force if it is held still with respect to the field.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] This is why a person will feel himself pulled down by the force of gravity while standing still on the Earth's surface.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-field] In general the gravitational fields predicted by general relativity differ in their effects only slightly from those predicted by classical mechanics, but there are a number of easily verifiable differences, one of the most well known being the deflection of light in such fields.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A **gravitational lens** is matter, such as a cluster of galaxies or a point particle, that bends light from a distant source as it travels toward an observer.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The amount of **gravitational lensing** is described by Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If light is treated as corpuscles travelling at the speed of light, Newtonian physics also predicts the bending of light, but only half of that predicted by general relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Orest Khvolson (1924) and Frantisek Link (1936) are generally credited with being the first to discuss the effect in print, but it is more commonly associated with Einstein, who made unpublished calculations on it in 1912 and published an article on the subject in 1936.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In 1937, Fritz Zwicky posited that galaxy clusters could act as gravitational lenses, a claim confirmed in 1979 by observation of the Twin QSO SBS 0957+561.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Unlike an optical lens, a point-like gravitational lens produces a maximum deflection of light that passes closest to its center, and a minimum deflection of light that travels furthest from its center.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Consequently, a gravitational lens has no single focal point, but a focal line.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The term "lens" in the context of gravitational light deflection was first used by O.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Lodge, who remarked that it is "not permissible to say that the solar gravitational field acts like a lens, for it has no focal length".
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If the (light) source, the massive lensing object, and the observer lie in a straight line, the original light source will appear as a ring around the massive lensing object (provided the lens has circular symmetry).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If there is any misalignment, the observer will see an arc segment instead.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This phenomenon was first mentioned in 1924 by the St.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Petersburg physicist Orest Khvolson, and quantified by Albert Einstein in 1936.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] It is usually referred to in the literature as an Einstein ring, since Khvolson did not concern himself with the flux or radius of the ring image.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] More commonly, where the lensing mass is complex (such as a galaxy group or cluster) and does not cause a spherical distortion of spacetime, the source will resemble partial arcs scattered around the lens.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The observer may then see multiple distorted images of the same source; the number and shape of these depending upon the relative positions of the source, lens, and observer, and the shape of the gravitational well of the lensing object.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] can produce separations of several arcminutes.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Where the distortions of background sources are much smaller and can only be detected by analyzing large numbers of sources in a statistical way to find coherent distortions of only a few percent.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The lensing shows up statistically as a preferred stretching of the background objects perpendicular to the direction to the centre of the lens.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Since galaxies are intrinsically elliptical and the weak gravitational lensing signal is small, a very large number of galaxies must be used in these surveys.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] to distort images must be understood and carefully accounted for.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] , and to provide a consistency check on other cosmological observations.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Where no distortion in shape can be seen but the amount of light received from a background object changes in time.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In extreme cases, a star in a distant galaxy can act as a microlens and magnify another star much farther away.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] (also known as Icarus), thanks to the boost in flux due to the microlensing effect.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Gravitational lenses act equally on all kinds of electromagnetic radiation, not just visible light, and also in non-electromagnetic radiation, like gravitational waves.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Weak lensing effects are being studied for the cosmic microwave background as well as galaxy surveys.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Strong lenses have been observed in radio and x-ray regimes as well.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If a strong lens produces multiple images, there will be a relative time delay between two paths: that is, in one image the lensed object will be observed before the other image.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The same value as Soldner's was calculated by Einstein in 1911 based on the equivalence principle alone.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] However, Einstein noted in 1915, in the process of completing general relativity, that his (and thus Soldner's) 1911-result is only half of the correct value.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Einstein became the first to calculate the correct value for light bending.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The first observation of light deflection was performed by noting the change in position of stars as they passed near the Sun on the celestial sphere.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The observations were performed in 1919 by Arthur Eddington, Frank Watson Dyson, and their collaborators during the total solar eclipse on May 29.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The solar eclipse allowed the stars near the Sun to be observed.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Observations were made simultaneously in the cities of Sobral, Ceará, Brazil and in São Tomé and Príncipe on the west coast of Africa.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The observations demonstrated that the light from stars passing close to the Sun was slightly bent, so that stars appeared slightly out of position.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The result was considered spectacular news and made the front page of most major newspapers.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] It made Einstein and his theory of general relativity world-famous.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] When asked by his assistant what his reaction would have been if general relativity had not been confirmed by Eddington and Dyson in 1919, Einstein said "Then I would feel sorry for the dear Lord.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The theory is correct anyway." In 1912, Einstein had speculated that an observer could see multiple images of a single light source, if the light were deflected around a mass.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This effect would make the mass act as a kind of gravitational lens.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] However, as he only considered the effect of deflection around a single star, he seemed to conclude that the phenomenon was unlikely to be observed for the foreseeable future since the necessary alignments between stars and observer would be highly improbable.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Several other physicists speculated about gravitational lensing as well, but all reached the same conclusion that it would be nearly impossible to observe.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Mandl, Einstein reluctantly published the short article "Lens-Like Action of a Star By the Deviation of Light In the Gravitational Field" in the journal *Science*.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In 1937, Fritz Zwicky first considered the case where the newly discovered galaxies (which were called 'nebulae' at the time) could act as both source and lens, and that, because of the mass and sizes involved, the effect was much more likely to be observed.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Liebes, and Sjur Refsdal recognized independently that quasars are an ideal light source for the gravitational lens effect.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] It was not until 1979 that the first gravitational lens would be discovered.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] It became known as the "Twin QSO" since it initially looked like two identical quasistellar objects.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] (It is officially named SBS 0957+561.) This gravitational lens was discovered by Dennis Walsh, Bob Carswell, and Ray Weymann using the Kitt Peak National Observatory 2.1 meter telescope.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In the 1980s, astronomers realized that the combination of CCD imagers and computers would allow the brightness of millions of stars to be measured each night.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In a dense field, such as the galactic center or the Magellanic clouds, many microlensing events per year could potentially be found.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This led to efforts such as Optical Gravitational Lensing Experiment, or OGLE, that have characterized hundreds of such events, including those of OGLE-2016-BLG-1190Lb and OGLE-2016-BLG-1195Lb.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Newton wondered whether light, in the form of corpuscles, would be bent due to gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] where r is the lens-corpuscle separation.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If one assumes that initially the light is far enough from the lens to neglect gravity, the perpendicular distance between the light's initial trajectory and the lens is *b* (the impact parameter), and the parallel distance is $r_{\parallel }$ , such that $r^{2}=b^{2}+r_{\parallel }^{2}$ .
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] We additionally assume a constant speed of light along the parallel direction, $dr_{\parallel }\approx c\,dt$ , and that the light is only being deflected a small amount.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] After plugging these assumptions into the above equation and further simplifying, one can solve for the velocity boost in the perpendicular direction.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The angle of deflection between the corpuscle's initial and final trajectories is therefore (see, e.g., M.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Although this result appears to be half the prediction from general relativity, classical physics predicts that the speed of light c is observer-dependent (see, e.g., L.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Friedman 2018) which was superseded by a universal speed of light in special relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In general relativity, light follows the curvature of spacetime, hence when light passes around a massive object, it is bent.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This means that the light from an object on the other side will be bent towards an observer's eye, just like an ordinary lens.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In general relativity the path of light depends on the shape of space (i.e. the metric).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The gravitational attraction can be viewed as the motion of undisturbed objects in a background curved *geometry* or alternatively as the response of objects to a *force* in a flat geometry.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] toward the mass *M* at a distance *r* from the affected radiation, where *G* is the universal constant of gravitation, and *c* is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Most of the gravitational lenses in the past have been discovered accidentally.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A search for gravitational lenses in the northern hemisphere (Cosmic Lens All Sky Survey, CLASS), done in radio frequencies using the Very Large Array (VLA) in New Mexico, led to the discovery of 22 new lensing systems, a major milestone.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This has opened a whole new avenue for research ranging from finding very distant objects to finding values for cosmological parameters so we can understand the universe better.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A similar search in the southern hemisphere would be a very good step towards complementing the northern hemisphere search as well as obtaining other objectives for study.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If such a search is done using well-calibrated and well-parameterized instruments and data, a result similar to the northern survey can be expected.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The use of the Australia Telescope 20 GHz (AT20G) Survey data collected using the Australia Telescope Compact Array (ATCA) stands to be such a collection of data.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] As the data were collected using the same instrument maintaining a very stringent quality of data we should expect to obtain good results from the search.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The AT20G survey is a blind survey at 20 GHz frequency in the radio domain of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Due to the high frequency used, the chances of finding gravitational lenses increases as the relative number of compact core objects (e.g. quasars) are higher (Sadler et al.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This is important as the lensing is easier to detect and identify in simple objects compared to objects with complexity in them.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This search involves the use of interferometric methods to identify candidates and follow them up at higher resolution to identify them.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Full detail of the project is currently under works for publication.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Recently launched and upcoming surveys will increase the number of confirmed gravitational lenses by orders of magnitude.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The European Space Agency (ESA) 2023 launch of the Euclid Space Telescope found around 500 strong-lens candidates in the first 0.45% of its full survey area, with an expected 100,000 candidates to be found during its 6-year survey.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Rubin Observatory (LSST) began data collection in 2025 in Cerro Pachón, Chile.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] LSST expects to discover around 62,000 to 120,000 galaxy-scale lenses over its 10-year survey.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The upcoming 2026/2027 launch of Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope, is expected to discover around 160,000 strong gravitational lenses through the planned High Latitude Wide Area Survey (HLWAS).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Microlensing techniques have been used to search for planets outside the Solar System.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A statistical analysis of specific cases of observed microlensing over the time period of 2002 to 2007 found that most stars in the Milky Way galaxy hosted at least one orbiting planet within 0.5 to 10 AU.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In 2009, weak gravitational lensing was used to extend the mass-X-ray-luminosity relation to older and smaller structures than was previously possible to improve measurements of distant galaxies.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] As of 2013 the most distant gravitational lens galaxy, J1000+0221, had been found using NASA's Hubble Space Telescope.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] While it remains the most distant quad-image lensing galaxy known, an even more distant two-image lensing galaxy was subsequently discovered by an international team of astronomers using a combination of Hubble Space Telescope and Keck telescope imaging and spectroscopy.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The discovery and analysis of the IRC 0218 lens was published in the *Astrophysical Journal Letters* on June 23, 2014.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In 2023, a massive galaxy with a complete Einstein ring at redshift z = 2 was identified in JWST NIRCam observations in the COSMOS-Web survey.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The object, named JWST-ER1, is located approximately 17 billion light-years away, making it the most distant lensing galaxy observed to date.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The compact, massive, quiescent galaxy (JWST-ER1g) is located at zphot ~ 1.94, lenses an even farther background galaxy (JWST-ER1r) at zphot ~ 2.98, creating the complete, luminous ring.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] JWST-ER1 is even more distant than the lenses mentioned above, J1000+0221 and IRC 0218, and its discovery and unusually high-density has important implications in understanding dark matter halos.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This discovery would open the possibilities of testing the theories of how our universe originated.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] revealed by gravitational lensing (16 October 2014).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Albert Einstein predicted in 1936 that rays of light from the same direction that skirt the edges of the Sun would converge to a focal point approximately 542 AU from the Sun.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Thus, a probe positioned at this distance (or greater) from the Sun could use the Sun as a gravitational lens for magnifying distant objects on the opposite side of the Sun.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A probe's location could shift around as needed to select different targets relative to the Sun.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This distance is far beyond the progress and equipment capabilities of space probes such as *Voyager 1*, and beyond the known planets and dwarf planets, though over thousands of years 90377 Sedna will move farther away on its highly elliptical orbit.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The high gain for potentially detecting signals through this lens, such as microwaves at the 21-cm hydrogen line, led to the suggestion by Frank Drake in the early days of SETI that a probe could be sent to this distance.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A multipurpose probe SETISAIL and later FOCAL was proposed to the ESA in 1993, but is expected to be a difficult task.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] If a probe does pass 542 AU, magnification capabilities of the lens will continue to act at farther distances, as the rays that come to a focus at larger distances pass further away from the distortions of the Sun's corona.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] A critique of the concept was given by Landis, who discussed issues including interference of the solar corona, the high magnification of the target, which will make the design of the mission focal plane difficult, and an analysis of the inherent spherical aberration of the lens.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] In 2020, NASA physicist Slava Turyshev presented his idea of Direct Multipixel Imaging and Spectroscopy of an Exoplanet with a Solar Gravitational Lens Mission.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The lens could reconstruct the exoplanet image with ~25 km-scale surface resolution, enough to see surface features and signs of habitability.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Kaiser, Squires and Broadhurst (1995), Luppino & Kaiser (1997) and Hoekstra et al.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] (1998) prescribed a method to invert the effects of the point spread function (PSF) smearing and shearing, recovering a shear estimator uncontaminated by the systematic distortion of the PSF.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This method (KSB+) is the most widely used method in weak lensing shear measurements.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] Galaxies have random rotations and inclinations.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] As a result, the shear effects in weak lensing need to be determined by statistically preferred orientations.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The primary source of error in lensing measurement is due to the convolution of the PSF with the lensed image.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The KSB method measures the ellipticity of a galaxy image.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The shear is proportional to the ellipticity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] The objects in lensed images are parameterized according to their weighted quadrupole moments.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] For a perfect ellipse, the weighted quadrupole moments are related to the weighted ellipticity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] KSB calculate how a weighted ellipticity measure is related to the shear and use the same formalism to remove the effects of the PSF.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] KSB's primary advantages are its mathematical ease and relatively simple implementation.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] However, KSB is based on a key assumption that the PSF is circular with an anisotropic distortion.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] This is a reasonable assumption for cosmic shear surveys, but the next generation of surveys (e.g.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-lens] LSST) may need much better accuracy than KSB can provide.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] In classical mechanics, the **gravitational potential** is a scalar potential associating with each point in space the work (energy transferred) per unit mass that would be needed to move an object to that point from a fixed reference point in the conservative gravitational field.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] It is analogous to the electric potential with mass playing the role of charge.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The reference point, where the potential is zero, is by convention infinitely far away from any mass, resulting in a negative potential at any finite distance.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Their similarity is correlated with both associated fields having conservative forces.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Mathematically, the gravitational potential is also known as the Newtonian potential and is fundamental in the study of potential theory.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] It may also be used for solving the electrostatic and magnetostatic fields generated by uniformly charged or polarized ellipsoidal bodies.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Potential energy is equal (in magnitude, but negative) to the work done by the gravitational field moving a body to its given position in space from infinity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] If the body has a mass of 1 kilogram, then the potential energy to be assigned to that body is equal to the gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] So the potential can be interpreted as the negative of the work done by the gravitational field moving a unit mass in from infinity.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] In some situations, the equations can be simplified by assuming a field that is nearly independent of position.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] For instance, in a region close to the surface of the Earth, the gravitational acceleration, *g*, can be considered constant.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The product *GM* is the standard gravitational parameter and is often known to higher precision than *G* or *M* separately.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The potential has units of energy per mass, e.g., J/kg in the MKS system.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] By convention, it is always negative where it is defined, and as *x* tends to infinity, it approaches zero.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The gravitational field, and thus the acceleration of a small body in the space around the massive object, is the negative gradient of the gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Thus the negative of a negative gradient yields positive acceleration toward a massive object.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The potential associated with a mass distribution is the superposition of the potentials of point masses.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] If the mass distribution is given as a mass measure *dm* on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3, then the potential is the convolution of −*G*/|**r**| with *dm*.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] If *V* is a potential function coming from a continuous mass distribution *ρ*(**r**), then *ρ* can be recovered using the Laplace operator, Δ: $\rho (\mathbf {x} )={\frac {1}{4\pi G}}\Delta V(\mathbf {x} ).$ This holds pointwise whenever *ρ* is continuous and is zero outside of a bounded set.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] In general, the mass measure *dm* can be recovered in the same way if the Laplace operator is taken in the sense of distributions.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] As a consequence, the gravitational potential satisfies Poisson's equation.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] See also Green's function for the three-variable Laplace equation and Newtonian potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The integral may be expressed in terms of known transcendental functions for all ellipsoidal shapes, including the symmetrical and degenerate ones.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] All these shapes are widely used in the applications of the gravitational potential integral (apart from the constant *G*, with 𝜌 being a constant charge density) to electromagnetism.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] A spherically symmetric mass distribution behaves to an observer completely outside the distribution as though all of the mass was concentrated at the center, and thus effectively as a point mass, by the shell theorem.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] On the surface of the earth, the acceleration is given by so-called standard gravity *g*, approximately 9.8 m/s2, although this value varies slightly with latitude and altitude.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The magnitude of the acceleration is a little larger at the poles than at the equator because Earth is an oblate spheroid.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Within a spherically symmetric mass distribution, it is possible to solve Poisson's equation in spherical coordinates.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] In general relativity, the gravitational potential is replaced by the metric tensor.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] When the gravitational field is weak and the sources are moving very slowly compared to light-speed, general relativity reduces to Newtonian gravity, and the metric tensor can be expanded in terms of the gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The potential can be expanded in a series of Legendre polynomials.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Represent the points **x** and **r** as position vectors relative to the center of mass.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] (See *§ Mathematical form*.) The integrand can be expanded as a Taylor series in *Z* = *r*/|**x**|, by explicit calculation of the coefficients.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] A less laborious way of achieving the same result is by using the generalized binomial theorem.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The coefficients *P**n* are the Legendre polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] Therefore, the Taylor coefficients of the integrand are given by the Legendre polynomials in *X* = cos *θ*.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] This shows that elongation of the body causes a lower potential in the direction of elongation, and a higher potential in perpendicular directions, compared to the potential due to a spherical mass, if we compare cases with the same distance to the center of mass.
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The SI unit of gravitational potential is the square metre per square second (m2/s2) or, equivalently, the joule per kilogram (J/kg).
[src:gravitation/gravitational-potential] The potential is half the square of the escape velocity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In physics, **gravity** (from Latin *gravitas* 'weight'), also known as **gravitation** or a **gravitational interaction**, is a fundamental interaction, which may be described as the force that draws material objects towards each other.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The gravitational attraction between clouds of primordial hydrogen and clumps of dark matter in the early universe caused the hydrogen gas to coalesce, eventually condensing and fusing to form stars.
[src:gravitation/gravity] At larger scales this resulted in galaxies and clusters, so gravity is a primary driver for the large-scale structures in the universe.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity has an infinite range, although its effects become weaker as objects get farther away.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity is described by the general theory of relativity, proposed by Albert Einstein in 1915, which describes gravity in terms of the curvature of spacetime, caused by the uneven distribution of mass.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The most extreme example of this curvature of spacetime is a black hole, from which nothing—not even light—can escape once past the black hole's event horizon.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Scientists are looking for a theory that describes gravity in the framework of quantum mechanics (quantum gravity), which would unify gravity and the other known fundamental interactions of physics in a single mathematical framework (a theory of everything).
[src:gravitation/gravity] On the surface of a planetary body such as on Earth, the force of gravity operates towards the center of the body and is modified by the centrifugal effects arising from the rotation of the body.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In this context, gravity gives weight to physical objects and is essential to understanding the mechanisms that are responsible for surface water waves, lunar tides and substantially contributes to weather patterns.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravitational weight also has many important biological functions, helping to guide the growth of plants through the process of gravitropism and influencing the circulation of fluids in multicellular organisms.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity is the word used to describe a physical law, a fundamental physical interaction that derives primarily from mass, and the observed consequences of that interaction on objects.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity is the law that every object with mass attracts every other object in the universe in proportion to each mass and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force of gravity, F is written using the gravitational constant, G, as $F=G{\frac {mm'}{r^{2}}}$ for two masses, m, and *m*′ separated by a distance r.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity is considered to be one of four fundamental interactions.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The electromagnetic force law is similar to the force law for gravity: both depend upon the square of the inverse distance between objects in typical interactions.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The ratio of gravitational attraction of two electrons to their electrical repulsion is 1 to 4.17×1042.
[src:gravitation/gravity] As a result, gravity can generally be neglected at the level of subatomic particles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity becomes the most significant interaction between objects at the scale of astronomical bodies, and it determines the motion of satellites, planets, stars, galaxies, and even light.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity is also fundamental in another sense: the inertial mass that appears in Newton's second law is the same as the gravitational mass.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This equivalence principle is a scientific hypothesis that has been tested experimentally to more than one part in a trillion.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The nature and mechanism of gravity were explored by a wide range of ancient scholars.
[src:gravitation/gravity] He also thought that the speed of a falling object should increase with its weight, a conclusion that was later shown to be false.
[src:gravitation/gravity] While Aristotle's view was widely accepted throughout Ancient Greece, there were other thinkers such as Plutarch who correctly predicted that the attraction of gravity was not unique to the Earth.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Although he did not understand gravity as a force, the ancient Greek philosopher Archimedes discovered the center of gravity of a triangle.
[src:gravitation/gravity] He postulated that if two equal weights did not have the same center of gravity, the center of gravity of the two weights together would be in the middle of the line that joins their centers of gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Two centuries later, the Roman engineer and architect Vitruvius contended in his *De architectura* that gravity is not dependent on a substance's weight but rather on its "nature".
[src:gravitation/gravity] In the 6th century CE, the Byzantine Alexandrian scholar John Philoponus proposed the theory of impetus, which modifies Aristotle's theory that "continuation of motion depends on continued action of a force" by incorporating a causative force that diminishes over time.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 628 CE, the Indian mathematician and astronomer Brahmagupta proposed the idea that gravity is an attractive force that draws objects to the Earth and used the term *gurutvākarṣaṇ* to describe it.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In the ancient Middle East, gravity was a topic of fierce debate.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The Persian intellectual Al-Biruni believed that the force of gravity was not unique to the Earth, and he correctly assumed that other heavenly bodies should exert a gravitational attraction as well.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In contrast, Al-Khazini held the same position as Aristotle that all matter in the Universe is attracted to the center of the Earth.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In the mid-16th century, various European scientists experimentally disproved the Aristotelian notion that heavier objects fall at a faster rate.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In particular, the Spanish Dominican priest Domingo de Soto wrote in 1551 that bodies in free fall uniformly accelerate.
[src:gravitation/gravity] De Soto may have been influenced by earlier experiments conducted by other Dominican priests in Italy, including those by Benedetto Varchi, Francesco Beato, Luca Ghini, and Giovan Bellaso which contradicted Aristotle's teachings on the fall of bodies.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The mid-16th century Italian physicist Giambattista Benedetti published papers claiming that, due to specific gravity, objects made of the same material but with different masses would fall at the same speed.
[src:gravitation/gravity] With the 1586 Delft tower experiment, the Flemish physicist Simon Stevin observed that two cannonballs of differing sizes and weights fell at the same rate when dropped from a tower.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In the late 16th century, Galileo Galilei's careful measurements of balls rolling down inclines allowed him to firmly establish that gravitational acceleration is the same for all objects.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Galileo postulated that air resistance is the reason that objects with a low density and high surface area fall more slowly in an atmosphere.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In his 1638 work *Two New Sciences*, Galileo proved that the distance traveled by a falling object is proportional to the square of the time elapsed.
[src:gravitation/gravity] His method was a form of graphical numerical integration since concepts of algebra and calculus were unknown at the time.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This was later confirmed by Italian scientists Grimaldi and Riccioli between 1640 and 1650.
[src:gravitation/gravity] They also calculated the magnitude of the Earth's gravity by measuring the oscillations of a pendulum.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Galileo also broke with incorrect ideas of Aristotelian philosophy by regarding inertia as persistence of motion, not a tendency to come to rest.
[src:gravitation/gravity] By considering that the laws of physics appear identical on a moving ship to those on land, Galileo developed the concepts of reference frame and the principle of relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] These concepts would become central to Newton's mechanics, only to be transformed in Einstein's theory of gravity, the general theory of relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In last quarter of the 16th century Tycho Brahe created accurate tools for astrometry, providing careful observations of the planets.
[src:gravitation/gravity] His assistant and successor, Johannes Kepler analyzed these data into three empirical laws of planetary motion.
[src:gravitation/gravity] These laws were central to the development of a theory of gravity a hundred years later.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In his 1609 book Astronomia nova Kepler described gravity as a mutual attraction, claiming that if the Earth and Moon were not held apart by some force they would come together.
[src:gravitation/gravity] He recognized that mechanical forces cause action, creating a kind of celestial machine.
[src:gravitation/gravity] On the other hand Kepler viewed the force of the Sun on the planets as magnetic and acting tangential to their orbits and he assumed with Aristotle that inertia meant objects tend to come to rest.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1666, Giovanni Alfonso Borelli avoided the key problems that limited Kepler.
[src:gravitation/gravity] By Borelli's time the concept of inertia had its modern meaning as the tendency of objects to remain in uniform motion and he viewed the Sun as just another heavenly body.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Borelli developed the idea of mechanical equilibrium, a balance between inertia and gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton cited Borelli's influence on his theory.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1657, Robert Hooke published his *Micrographia*, in which he hypothesized that the Moon must have its own gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In a communication to the Royal Society in 1666 and his 1674 Gresham lecture, *An Attempt to prove the Annual Motion of the Earth*, Hooke took the important step of combining related hypothesis and then forming predictions based on the hypothesis.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Hooke was an important communicator who helped reformulate the scientific enterprise.
[src:gravitation/gravity] He was one of the first professional scientists and worked as the then-new Royal Society's curator of experiments for 40 years.
[src:gravitation/gravity] However his valuable insights remained hypotheses and some of these were incorrect.
[src:gravitation/gravity] He was unable to develop a mathematical theory of gravity and work out the consequences.
[src:gravitation/gravity] For this he turned to Newton, writing him a letter in 1679, outlining a model of planetary motion in a void or vacuum due to attractive action at a distance.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This letter likely turned Newton's thinking in a new direction leading to his revolutionary work on gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] When Newton reported his results in 1686, Hooke claimed the inverse square law portion was his "notion".
[src:gravitation/gravity] Before 1684, scientists including Christopher Wren, Robert Hooke and Edmund Halley determined that Kepler's third law, relating to planetary orbital periods, would prove the inverse square law if the orbits were circles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] However the orbits were known to be ellipses.
[src:gravitation/gravity] At Halley's suggestion, Newton tackled the problem and was able to prove that ellipses also proved the inverse square relation from Kepler's observations.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1684, Isaac Newton sent a manuscript to Edmond Halley titled *De motu corporum in gyrum ('On the motion of bodies in an orbit')*, which provided a physical justification for Kepler's laws of planetary motion.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Halley was impressed by the manuscript and urged Newton to expand on it, and a few years later Newton published a groundbreaking book called *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (*Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy*).
[src:gravitation/gravity] The revolutionary aspect of Newton's theory of gravity was the unification of Earth-bound observations of acceleration with celestial mechanics.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In his book, Newton described gravitation as a universal force, and claimed that it operated on objects "according to the quantity of solid matter which they contain and propagates on all sides to immense distances always at the inverse square of the distances".
[src:gravitation/gravity] This formulation had two important parts.
[src:gravitation/gravity] First was equating inertial mass and gravitational mass.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's 2nd law defines force via $F=ma$ for inertial mass, his law of gravitational force uses the same mass.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton did experiments with pendulums to verify this concept as best he could.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The second aspect of Newton's formulation was the inverse square of distance.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This aspect was not new: the astronomer Ismaël Bullialdus proposed it around 1640.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Seeking proof, Newton made quantitative analysis around 1665, considering the period and distance of the Moon's orbit and considering the timing of objects falling on Earth.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton did not publish these results at the time because he could not prove that the Earth's gravity acts as if all its mass were concentrated at its center.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's *Principia* was well received by the scientific community, and his law of gravitation quickly spread across the European world.
[src:gravitation/gravity] More than a century later, in 1821, his theory of gravitation rose to even greater prominence when it was used to predict the existence of Neptune.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In that year, the French astronomer Alexis Bouvard used this theory to create a table modeling the orbit of Uranus, which was shown to differ significantly from the planet's actual trajectory.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In order to explain this discrepancy, many astronomers speculated that there might be a large object beyond the orbit of Uranus which was disrupting its orbit.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1846, the astronomers John Couch Adams and Urbain Le Verrier independently used Newton's law to predict Neptune's location in the night sky, and the planet was discovered there within a day.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's formulation was later condensed into the inverse-square law: $F=G{\frac {m_{1}m_{2}}{r^{2}}},$ where F is the force, *m*1 and *m*2 are the masses of the objects interacting, r is the distance between the centers of the masses and *G* is the gravitational constant 6.674×10−11 m3⋅kg−1⋅s−2.
[src:gravitation/gravity] While *G* is also called Newton's constant, Newton did not use this constant or formula, he only discussed proportionality.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The value of *G* was eventually measured by Henry Cavendish in 1797.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's theory of gravity ran counter to a key idea of science, both then and now: forces should not rely on instantaneous action at a distance.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton was well aware of this issue and his decision to continue anyway marked a shift in scientific thinking away from philosophically sound but empirically flawed models.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Scientists like Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz complained about this aspect of the theory of gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The issue was not resolved until Einstein's work on relativity in the 20th century.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Eventually, astronomers noticed an eccentricity in the orbit of the planet Mercury which could not be explained by Newton's theory: the perihelion of the orbit was increasing by about 42.98 arcseconds per century.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The most obvious explanation for this discrepancy was an as-yet-undiscovered celestial body, such as a planet orbiting the Sun even closer than Mercury, but all efforts to find such a body turned out to be fruitless.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1915, Albert Einstein developed a theory of general relativity which was able to accurately model Mercury's orbit.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Einstein's theory brought two other ideas with independent histories into the physical theories of gravity: the principle of relativity and non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The principle of relativity, introduced by Galileo and used as a foundational principle by Newton, led to a long and fruitless search for a luminiferous aether after Maxwell's equations demonstrated that light propagated at a fixed speed independent of reference frame.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In Newton's mechanics, velocities add: a cannon ball shot from a moving ship would travel with a trajectory which included the motion of the ship.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Since light speed was fixed, it was assumed to travel in a fixed, absolute medium.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Many experiments sought to reveal this medium but failed and in 1905 Einstein's special relativity theory showed the aether was not needed.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Special relativity proposed that mechanics be reformulated to use the Lorentz transformation already applicable to light rather than the Galilean transformation adopted by Newton.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Special relativity, as in special case, specifically did not cover gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] While relativity was associated with mechanics and thus gravity, the idea of altering geometry only joined the story of gravity once mechanics required the Lorentz transformations.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gauss' student Bernhard Riemann developed this into a complete geometry by 1854.
[src:gravitation/gravity] These geometries are locally flat but have global curvature.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1907, Einstein took his first step by using special relativity to create a new form of the equivalence principle.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The equivalence of inertial mass and gravitational mass was a known empirical law.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The m in Newton's first law, $F=ma$ , has the same value as the m in Newton's law of gravity on Earth, $F=GMm/r^{2}$ .
[src:gravitation/gravity] In what he later described as "the happiest thought of my life" Einstein realized this meant that in free-fall, an accelerated coordinate system exists with no local gravitational field.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Every description of gravity in any other coordinate system must transform to give no field in the free-fall case, a powerful invariance constraint on all theories of gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Einstein's description of gravity was accepted by the majority of physicists for two reasons.
[src:gravitation/gravity] First, by 1910 his special relativity was accepted in German physics and was spreading to other countries.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Second, his theory explained experimental results like the perihelion of Mercury and the bending of light around the Sun better than Newton's theory.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1919, the British astrophysicist Arthur Eddington was able to confirm the predicted deflection of light during that year's solar eclipse.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Eddington measured starlight deflections twice those predicted by Newtonian corpuscular theory, in accordance with the predictions of general relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Although Eddington's analysis was later disputed, this experiment made Einstein famous almost overnight and caused general relativity to become widely accepted in the scientific community.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1959, American physicists Robert Pound and Glen Rebka performed an experiment in which they used gamma rays to confirm the prediction of gravitational time dilation.
[src:gravitation/gravity] By sending the rays down a 74-foot tower and measuring their frequency at the bottom, the scientists confirmed that light is Doppler shifted as it moves towards a source of gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The observed shift also supports the idea that time runs more slowly in the presence of a gravitational field (many more wave crests pass in a given interval).
[src:gravitation/gravity] If light moves outward from a strong source of gravity it will be observed with a redshift.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The time delay of light passing close to a massive object was first identified by Irwin I.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Shapiro in 1964 in interplanetary spacecraft signals.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 1971, scientists made the first-ever discovery of a black hole, in the constellation Cygnus.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The black hole was detected because it was emitting bursts of x-rays as it consumed a smaller star, and it came to be known as Cygnus X-1.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This discovery confirmed yet another prediction of general relativity, because Einstein's equations implied that light could not escape from a sufficiently large and compact object.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Frame dragging, the idea that a rotating massive object should twist spacetime around it, was confirmed by Gravity Probe B results in 2011.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In 2015, the LIGO observatory detected faint gravitational waves, the existence of which had been predicted by general relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Scientists believe that the waves emanated from a black hole merger that occurred 1.5 billion light-years away.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Every planetary body (including the Earth) is surrounded by its own gravitational field, which can be conceptualized with Newtonian physics as exerting an attractive force on all objects.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Assuming a spherically symmetrical planet, the strength of this field at any given point above the surface is proportional to the planetary body's mass and inversely proportional to the square of the distance from the center of the body.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The strength of the gravitational field is numerically equal to the acceleration of objects under its influence.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The rate of acceleration of falling objects near the Earth's surface varies very slightly depending on latitude, surface features such as mountains and ridges, and perhaps unusually high or low sub-surface densities.
[src:gravitation/gravity] For purposes of weights and measures, a standard gravity value is defined by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures, under the International System of Units (SI).
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force of gravity experienced by objects on Earth's surface is the vector sum of two forces: (a) The gravitational attraction in accordance with Newton's universal law of gravitation, and (b) the centrifugal force, which results from the choice of an earthbound, rotating frame of reference.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force of gravity is weakest at the equator because of the centrifugal force caused by the Earth's rotation and because points on the equator are farthest from the center of the Earth.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force of gravity varies with latitude, and the resultant acceleration increases from about 9.780 m/s2 at the Equator to about 9.832 m/s2 at the poles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Waves on oceans, lakes, and other bodies of water occur when the gravitational equilibrium at the surface of the water is disturbed by for example wind.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Similar effects occur in the atmosphere where equilibrium is disturbed by thermal weather fronts or mountain ranges.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Planets orbit the Sun in an ellipse as a consequence of the law of gravity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Similarly the Moon and artificial satellites orbit the Earth.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Conceptually two objects in orbit are both falling off of the curve they would travel in if the force of gravity were not pulling them together.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Since the force of gravity is universal, all planets attract each other with the most massive and closest pair have the most mutual affect.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This means orbits are more complex than simple ellipses.
[src:gravitation/gravity] During star formation, gravitational attraction in a cloud of hydrogen gas competes with thermal gas pressure.
[src:gravitation/gravity] As the gas density increases, the temperature rises, then the gas radiates energy, allowing additional gravitational condensation.
[src:gravitation/gravity] If the mass of gas in the region is low, the process continues until a brown dwarf or gas-giant planet is produced.
[src:gravitation/gravity] If more mass is available, the additional gravitational energy allows the central region to reach pressures sufficient for nuclear fusion, forming a star.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In a star, again the gravitational attraction competes, with thermal and radiation pressure in hydrostatic equilibrium until the star's atomic fuel runs out.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The next phase depends upon the total mass of the star.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Very low mass stars slowly cool as white dwarf stars with a small core balancing gravitational attraction with electron degeneracy pressure.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Stars with masses similar to the Sun go through a red giant phase before becoming white dwarf stars.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Higher mass stars have complex core structures that burn helium and high atomic number elements ultimately producing an iron core.
[src:gravitation/gravity] As their fuel runs out, these stars become unstable producing a supernova.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The result can be a neutron star where gravitational attraction balances neutron degeneracy pressure or, for even higher masses, a black hole where gravity operates alone with such intensity that even light cannot escape.
[src:gravitation/gravity] General relativity predicts that energy can be transported out of a system through gravitational radiation also known as gravitational waves.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The first indirect evidence for gravitational radiation was through measurements of the Hulse–Taylor binary in 1973.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This system consists of a pulsar and neutron star in orbit around one another.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Its orbital period has decreased since its initial discovery due to a loss of energy, which is consistent for the amount of energy loss due to gravitational radiation.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This research was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1993.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The first direct evidence for gravitational radiation was measured on 14 September 2015 by the LIGO detectors.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The gravitational waves emitted during the collision of two black holes 1.3 billion light years from Earth were measured.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This observation confirms the theoretical predictions of Einstein and others that such waves exist.
[src:gravitation/gravity] It also opens the way for practical observation and understanding of the nature of gravity and events in the Universe including the Big Bang.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Neutron star and black hole formation also create detectable amounts of gravitational radiation.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This research was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2017.
[src:gravitation/gravity] At the cosmological scale, gravity is a dominant player.
[src:gravitation/gravity] About 5/6 of the total mass in the universe consists of dark matter which interacts through gravity but not through electromagnetic interactions.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The gravitation of clumps of dark matter known as dark matter halos attract hydrogen gas leading to stars and galaxies.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravity acts on light and matter equally, meaning that a sufficiently massive object could warp light around it and create a gravitational lens.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This phenomenon was first confirmed by observation in 1979 using the 2.1 meter telescope at Kitt Peak National Observatory in Arizona, which saw two mirror images of the same quasar whose light had been bent around the galaxy YGKOW G1.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Many subsequent observations of gravitational lensing provide additional evidence for substantial amounts of dark matter around galaxies.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Gravitational lenses do not focus like eyeglass lenses, but rather lead to annular shapes called Einstein rings.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In October 2017, the LIGO and Virgo interferometer detectors received gravitational wave signals 2 seconds before gamma ray satellites and optical telescopes seeing signals from the same direction, from a source about 130 million light-years away.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This confirmed that the speed of gravitational waves was the same as the speed of light.
[src:gravitation/gravity] There are some observations that are not adequately accounted for, which may point to the need for better theories of gravity or perhaps be explained in other ways.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The physical models of gravity, like all physical models, are expressed mathematically.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Physicists use several different models, depending on the problem to be solved or for the purpose of gaining physical intuition.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's inverse square law models gravity as a force F between two objects proportional to their mass, m: $F_{12}=G{\frac {m_{1}m_{2}}{{r_{12}}^{2}}}$ This gravitational force causes the objects to accelerate towards each other unless balanced by other forces.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force is "nonlocal": it depends on the mass of an object at a distance.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Scientists from Newton onwards recognized that this action at a distance does not explain the root cause of the force; this lack of a root cause was raised against Newton's theory at first.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Nevertheless the model explains a vast number of physical effects including cannon ball trajectories, tidal motion and planetary orbits.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Creating a theory independent of action at a distance requires combining the concept of relativity with gravity, an enormously complex task using the Newtonian model.
[src:gravitation/gravity] A second equivalent approach to model gravity uses fields.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In physics, a field represents a physical phenomenon using a mathematical entity associated with each point in a space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Different field theories use different entities and concepts of space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] For classical field theories of gravity, the entities can be vectors associated with points in a 3-dimensional space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Each vector gives the force experienced by an insignificantly small test mass at that point in space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The force vector at each point can be computed as the direction of the highest rate of change in the gravitational potential, a single number at each point in space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The three-dimensional map of the potential or of the gravitational field provides a visual representation of the effect of the gravitational effect of all surrounding objects.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Field models are local: the field values on a sphere completely determine the effects of gravity with the sphere.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Fields are also used in general relativity, but rather than vectors over Euclidean space, the entities are tensors over spacetime.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The Einstein field equations relate the 10 independent values in the tensors to the distribution of mass and energy in space.
[src:gravitation/gravity] A third completely different way to derive a model of gravity is based on action principles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This formulation represents the effects of gravity on a system in a mathematically abstract way.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The state of the system, for example the position and velocity of every particle, is expressed as a single mathematical entity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Each state has an associated energy property called the Lagrangian; the physically allowed changes to the state of the system minimize the value of this property.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The path of the state is not a path in physical space, but rather in a high-dimensional state space: each point along the path corresponds to a different position and or velocity collectively for all particles in the system.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This formulation does not express the forces or fields of the individual particles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Modern theories of physics rely on these action principles.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The Einstein field equation for gravitation can be derived from the Einstein–Hilbert action.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In modern physics, general relativity is considered the most successful theory of gravitation.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Physicists continue to work to find solutions to the Einstein field equations that form the basis of general relativity and continue to test the theory, finding excellent agreement in all cases.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Any theory of gravity must conform to the requirements of special relativity and experimental observations.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Newton's theory of gravity assumes action at a distance and therefore cannot be reconciled with special relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The simplest generalization of Newton's approach would be a scalar field theory with the gravitational potential represented by a single number in a 4-dimensional spacetime.
[src:gravitation/gravity] However, this type of theory fails to predict gravitational redshift or the deviation of light by matter and gives values for the precession of Mercury which are incorrect.
[src:gravitation/gravity] A vector field theory predicts negative energy gravitational waves so it also fails.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Furthermore, no theory without curvature in spacetime can be consistent with special relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The simplest theory consistent with special relativity and the well-studied observations is general relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Unlike Newton's formula with one parameter, *G*, force in general relativity is terms of 10 numbers formed in to a metric tensor.In general relativity the effects of gravitation are described in different ways in different frames of reference.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In a free-falling or co-moving coordinate system, an object travels in a straight line.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In other coordinate systems, the object accelerates and thus is seen to move under a force.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The path in spacetime (not 3D space) taken by a free-falling object is called a geodesic and the length of that path as measured by time in the objects frame is the shortest (or rarely the longest) one.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Consequently the effect of gravity can be described as curving spacetime.
[src:gravitation/gravity] In a weak stationary gravitational field, general relativity reduces to Newton's equations.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The corrections introduced by general relativity on Earth are on the order of 1 part in a billion.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The Einstein field equations are a system of 10 partial differential equations which describe how matter affects the curvature of spacetime.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The system may be expressed in the form $G_{\mu \nu }+\Lambda g_{\mu \nu }=\kappa T_{\mu \nu },$ where Gμν is the Einstein tensor, gμν is the metric tensor, Tμν is the stress–energy tensor, Λ is the cosmological constant, G is the Newtonian constant of gravitation and c is the speed of light.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The constant $\kappa ={\frac {8\pi G}{c^{4}}}$ is referred to as the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The non-linear second-order Einstein field equations are extremely complex and have been solved in only a few special cases.
[src:gravitation/gravity] These cases however have been transformational in our understanding of the cosmos.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Several solutions are the basis for understanding black holes and for our modern model of the evolution of the universe since the Big Bang.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Testing the predictions of general relativity has historically been difficult, because they are almost identical to the predictions of Newtonian gravity for small energies and masses.
[src:gravitation/gravity] A wide range of experiments provided support of general relativity.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Today, Einstein's theory of relativity is used for all gravitational calculations where absolute precision is desired, although Newton's inverse-square law is accurate enough for virtually all ordinary calculations.
[src:gravitation/gravity] Despite its success in predicting the effects of gravity at large scales, general relativity is ultimately incompatible with quantum mechanics.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This is because general relativity describes gravity as a smooth, continuous distortion of spacetime, while quantum mechanics holds that all forces arise from the exchange of discrete particles known as quanta.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This contradiction is especially vexing to physicists because the other three fundamental forces (strong force, weak force and electromagnetism) were reconciled with a quantum framework decades ago.
[src:gravitation/gravity] As a result, researchers have begun to search for a theory that could unite both gravity and quantum mechanics under a more general framework.
[src:gravitation/gravity] One path is to describe gravity in the framework of quantum field theory (QFT), which has been successful to accurately describe the other fundamental interactions.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The electromagnetic force arises from an exchange of virtual photons, where the QFT description of gravity is that there is an exchange of virtual gravitons.
[src:gravitation/gravity] This description reproduces general relativity in the classical limit.
[src:gravitation/gravity] However, this approach fails at short distances of the order of the Planck length, where a more complete theory of quantum gravity (or a new approach to quantum mechanics) is required.
[src:gravitation/gravity] General relativity has withstood many tests over a large range of mass and size scales.
[src:gravitation/gravity] When applied to interpret astronomical observations, cosmological models based on general relativity introduce two components to the universe, dark matter and dark energy, the nature of which is currently an unsolved problem in physics.
[src:gravitation/gravity] The many successful, high precision predictions of the standard model of cosmology has led astrophysicists to conclude it and thus general relativity will be the basis for future progress.
[src:gravitation/gravity] However, dark matter is not supported by the Standard Model of particle physics, physical models for dark energy do not match cosmological data, and some cosmological observations are inconsistent.
[src:gravitation/gravity] These issues have led to the study of alternative theories of gravity.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] This is a general physical law derived from empirical observations by what Isaac Newton called *inductive reasoning*.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It is a part of classical mechanics and was formulated in Newton's work *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (Latin for 'Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy' (the *Principia*)), first published on 5 July 1687.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The first test of Newton's law of gravitation between masses in the laboratory was the Cavendish experiment conducted by the British scientist Henry Cavendish in 1798.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It took place 111 years after the publication of Newton's *Principia* and approximately 71 years after his death.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton's law of gravitation resembles Coulomb's law of electrical forces, which is used to calculate the magnitude of the electrical force arising between two charged bodies.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Both are inverse-square laws, where force is inversely proportional to the square of the distance between the bodies.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Coulomb's law has charge in place of mass and a different constant.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton's law was later superseded by Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity, but the universality of the gravitational constant is intact and the law still continues to be used as an excellent approximation of the effects of gravity in most applications.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Relativity is required only when there is a need for extreme accuracy, or when dealing with very strong gravitational fields, such as those found near extremely massive and dense objects, or at small distances (such as Mercury's orbit around the Sun).
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Before Newton's law of gravity, there were many theories explaining gravity.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Philosophers made observations about things falling down − and developed theories why they do – as early as Aristotle who thought that rocks fall to the ground because seeking the ground was an essential part of their nature.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Around 1600, the scientific method began to take root.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] René Descartes started over with a more fundamental view, developing ideas of matter and action independent of theology.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Galileo Galilei wrote about experimental measurements of falling and rolling objects.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Johannes Kepler's laws of planetary motion summarized Tycho Brahe's astronomical observations.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Around 1666, Isaac Newton developed the idea that Kepler's laws must also apply to the orbit of the Moon around the Earth and then to all objects on Earth.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The analysis required assuming that the gravitation force acted as if all of the mass of the Earth were concentrated at its center, an unproven conjecture at that time.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] His calculations of the Moon orbit time was within 16% of the known value.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] By 1680, new values for the diameter of the Earth improved his orbit time to within 1.6%, but more importantly Newton had found a proof of his earlier conjecture.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In 1687, Newton published his *Principia* which combined his laws of motion with new mathematical analysis to explain Kepler's empirical results.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton made quantitative analysis based on this formula around 1665, considering the period and distance of the Moon's orbit and considering the timing of objects falling on Earth.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] When Newton presented Book 1 of the unpublished text in April 1686 to the Royal Society, Robert Hooke made a claim that Newton had obtained the inverse square law from him, ultimately a frivolous accusation.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] While Newton was able to formulate his law of gravity in his monumental work, he was deeply uncomfortable with the notion of "action at a distance" that his equations implied.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The last sentence is Newton's famous and highly debated Latin phrase Hypotheses non fingo.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In other translations it comes out "I feign no hypotheses".
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton made two predictions based on his gravitational theory.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In 1774 the Schiehallion experiment compared the gravitational attraction of the Earth to that of Schiehallion mountain, confirming one of these predictions.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The second prediction concerned the mutual attraction of two massive spheres, confirmed by Henry Cavendish in 1798.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The value of the constant *G* was first accurately determined from the results of the Cavendish experiment conducted by the British scientist Henry Cavendish in 1798, although Cavendish did not himself calculate a numerical value for *G*.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] This experiment was also the first test of Newton's theory of gravitation between masses in the laboratory.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It took place 111 years after the publication of Newton's *Principia* and 71 years after Newton's death, so none of Newton's calculations could use the value of *G*; instead he could only calculate a force relative to another force.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] If the bodies in question have spatial extent (as opposed to being point masses), then the gravitational force between them is calculated by summing the contributions of the notional point masses that constitute the bodies.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In the limit, as the component point masses become "infinitely small", this entails integrating the force (in vector form, see below) over the extents of the two bodies.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In this way, it can be shown that an object with a spherically symmetric distribution of mass exerts the same gravitational attraction on external bodies as if all the object's mass were concentrated at a point at its center.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] For points *inside* a spherically symmetric distribution of matter, Newton's shell theorem can be used to find the gravitational force.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] As a consequence, for example, within a shell of uniform thickness and density there is *no net* gravitational acceleration anywhere within the hollow sphere.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton's law of universal gravitation can be written as a vector equation to account for the direction of the gravitational force as well as its magnitude.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It can be seen that the vector form of the equation is the same as the scalar form given earlier, except that **F** is now a vector quantity, and the right hand side is multiplied by the appropriate unit vector.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The **gravitational field** is a vector field that describes the gravitational force that would be applied on an object in any given point in space, per unit mass.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It is actually equal to the gravitational acceleration at that point.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] It is a generalisation of the vector form, which becomes particularly useful if more than two objects are involved (such as a rocket between the Earth and the Moon).
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] This formulation is dependent on the objects causing the field.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The field has the dimension of acceleration; in the SI, its unit is m/s2.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Gravitational fields are also conservative; that is, the work done by gravity from one position to another is path-independent.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] If *m*1 is a point mass or the mass of a sphere with homogeneous mass distribution, the force field **g**(**r**) outside the sphere is isotropic, i.e., depends only on the distance *r* from the center of the sphere.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] where $\partial V$ is a closed surface and $M_{\text{enc}}$ is the mass enclosed by the surface.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Newton's description of gravity is sufficiently accurate for many practical purposes and is therefore widely used.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] Deviations from it are small when the dimensionless quantities $\phi /c^{2}$ and $(v/c)^{2}$ are both much less than one, where $\phi$ is the gravitational potential, v is the velocity of the objects being studied, and c is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In situations where either dimensionless parameter is large, then general relativity must be used to describe the system.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] General relativity reduces to Newtonian gravity in the limit of small potential and low velocities, so Newton's law of gravitation is often said to be the low-gravity limit of general relativity.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The first two conflicts with observations above were explained by Einstein's theory of general relativity, in which gravitation is a manifestation of curved spacetime instead of being due to a force propagated between bodies.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In Einstein's theory, energy and momentum distort spacetime in their vicinity, and other particles move in trajectories determined by the geometry of spacetime.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] This allowed a description of the motions of light and mass that was consistent with all available observations.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In general relativity, the gravitational force is a fictitious force resulting from the curvature of spacetime, because the gravitational acceleration of a body in free fall is due to its world line being a geodesic of spacetime.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] In recent years, quests for non-inverse square terms in the law of gravity have been carried out by neutron interferometry.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The problem of predicting the motion of *n* objects subject to gravity is known as the *n*-body problem.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The two-body problem has been completely solved, but for more bodies the solution is in general chaotic and can only be obtained numerically.
[src:gravitation/newton-s-law-of-universal-gravitation] The most-studied case is the three-body problem, for which several solutions for particular cases are known, for example those giving rise to the Lagrange points.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The **tidal force** or **tide-generating force** is the difference in gravitational attraction between different points in a gravitational field.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] It causes different parts of bodies to be pulled unevenly, so that those bodies are being stretched towards the attraction.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal force is the **differential effect** of gravity across an extended body.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Rather than the total gravitational force, it is the spatial variation in that force.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Equivalently, it is the gradient of the gravitational field or the derivative of the gravitational potential.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces are therefore a **residual effect** of gravity, arising because the near side of a body experiences a stronger attraction than the more distant far side.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] This produces a range of tidal phenomena, such as ocean tides.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Earth's tides are mainly produced by the relative close gravitational field of the Moon and to a lesser extent by the stronger, but further away gravitational field of the Sun.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The ocean on the side of Earth facing the Moon is being pulled by the gravity of the Moon away from Earth's crust, while on the other side of Earth there the crust is being pulled away from the ocean, resulting in Earth being stretched, bulging on both sides, and having opposite high-tides.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces viewed from Earth, that is from a rotating reference frame, appear as centripetal and centrifugal forces, but are not caused by the rotation.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Further tidal phenomena include solid-earth tides, tidal locking, breaking apart of celestial bodies and formation of ring systems within the Roche limit, and in extreme cases, spaghettification of objects.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces have also been shown to be fundamentally related to gravitational waves.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The perturbing force is sometimes in such cases called a tidal force (for example, the perturbing force on the Moon): it is the difference between the force exerted by the third body on the second and the force exerted by the third body on the first.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] When a body **O** is acted on by the gravity of another body **S**, the field can vary significantly between the sides of **O** facing away and towards **S**.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Figure 2 shows the differential force of gravity in red, which can be derived by subtracting the body's overall force vector (shown in blue at the center) from the force vectors at the points of interest (shown in blue along the surface).
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] These *tidal forces* cause strains on both bodies and may distort them or even, in extreme cases, break one or the other apart.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The Roche limit is the distance from a planet at which tidal effects would cause an object to disintegrate because the differential force of gravity from the planet overcomes the attraction of the parts of the object for one another.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] These strains would not occur if the gravitational field were uniform, because a uniform field only causes the entire body to accelerate together in the same direction and at the same rate.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The relationship of an astronomical body's size, to its distance from another body, strongly influences the magnitude of tidal force.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The tidal force acting on an astronomical body, such as the Earth, is directly proportional to the diameter of the Earth and inversely proportional to the cube of the distance from another body producing a gravitational attraction, such as the Moon or the Sun.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal action on bath tubs, swimming pools, lakes, and other small bodies of water is negligible.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Figure 3 is a graph showing how gravitational force declines with distance.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] In this graph, the attractive force decreases in proportion to the square of the distance (*Y* = 1/*X*2), while the slope (*Y*′ = −2/*X*3) is inversely proportional to the cube of the distance.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The tidal force corresponds to the difference in Y between two points on the graph, with one point on the near side of the body, and the other point on the far side.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The tidal force becomes larger, when the two points are either farther apart, or when they are more to the left on the graph, meaning closer to the attracting body.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] For example, even though the Sun has a stronger overall gravitational pull on Earth, the Moon creates a larger tidal bulge because the Moon is closer.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] This difference is due to the way gravity weakens with distance: the Moon's closer proximity creates a steeper decline in its gravitational pull as you move across Earth (compared to the Sun's very gradual decline from its vast distance).
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] This steeper gradient in the Moon's pull results in a larger difference in force between the near and far sides of Earth, which is what creates the bigger tidal bulge.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Gravitational attraction is inversely proportional to the square of the distance from the source.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The attraction will be stronger on the side of a body facing the source, and weaker on the side away from the source.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The tidal force is proportional to the difference.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The Sun is about 20 million times the Moon's mass, and acts on the Earth over a distance about 400 times larger than that of the Moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Because of the cubic dependence on distance, this results in the solar tidal force on the Earth being about half that of the lunar tidal force.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] In the case of an infinitesimally small elastic sphere, the effect of a tidal force is to distort the shape of the body without any change in volume.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The sphere becomes an ellipsoid with two bulges, pointing towards and away from the other body.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Larger objects distort into an ovoid, and are slightly compressed, which is what happens to the Earth's oceans under the action of the Moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] All parts of the Earth are subject to the Moon's gravitational forces, causing the water in the oceans to redistribute, forming bulges on the sides near the Moon and far from the Moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] When a body rotates while subject to tidal forces, internal friction results in the gradual dissipation of its rotational kinetic energy as heat.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] In the case for the Earth, and Earth's Moon, the loss of rotational kinetic energy results in a gain of about 2 milliseconds per century.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] If the body is close enough to its primary, this can result in a rotation which is tidally locked to the orbital motion, as in the case of the Earth's moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal heating produces dramatic volcanic effects on Jupiter's moon Io.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Stresses caused by tidal forces also cause a regular monthly pattern of moonquakes on Earth's Moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces contribute to ocean currents, which moderate global temperatures by transporting heat energy toward the poles.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] It has been suggested that variations in tidal forces correlate with cool periods in the global temperature record at 6- to 10-year intervals, and that harmonic beat variations in tidal forcing may contribute to millennial climate changes.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] No strong link to millennial climate changes has been found to date.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal effects become particularly pronounced near small bodies of high mass, such as neutron stars or black holes, where they are responsible for the "spaghettification" of infalling matter.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces create the oceanic tide of Earth's oceans, where the attracting bodies are the Moon and, to a lesser extent, the Sun.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal forces are also responsible for tidal locking, tidal acceleration, and tidal heating.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] By generating conducting fluids within the interior of the Earth, tidal forces also affect the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Correspondingly, the term *tidal force* is used to describe the forces due to tidal acceleration.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Note that for these purposes the only gravitational field considered is the external one; the gravitational field of the body (as shown in the graphic) is not relevant.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] (In other words, the comparison is with the conditions at the given point as they would be if there were no externally generated field acting unequally at the given point and at the center of the reference body.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal acceleration does not require rotation or orbiting bodies; for example, the body may be freefalling in a straight line under the influence of a gravitational field while still being influenced by (changing) tidal acceleration.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] where ${\textstyle {\hat {r}}}$ is a unit vector pointing from the body *M* to the body *m* (here, acceleration from *m* towards *M* has negative sign).
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Consider now the acceleration due to the sphere of mass *M* experienced by a particle in the vicinity of the body of mass *m*.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] With *R* as the distance from the center of *M* to the center of *m*, let ∆*r* be the (relatively small) distance of the particle from the center of the body of mass *m*.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] For simplicity, distances are first considered only in the direction pointing towards or away from the sphere of mass *M*.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] If the body of mass *m* is itself a sphere of radius ∆*r*, then the new particle considered may be located on its surface, at a distance (*R* ± *∆r*) from the centre of the sphere of mass *M*, and *∆r* may be taken as positive where the particle's distance from *M* is greater than *R*.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The first term is the gravitational acceleration due to *M* at the center of the reference body ${\textstyle m}$ , i.e., at the point where ${\textstyle \Delta r}$ is zero.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] This term does not affect the observed acceleration of particles on the surface of *m* because with respect to *M*, *m* (and everything on its surface) is in free fall.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] When the force on the far particle is subtracted from the force on the near particle, this first term cancels, as do all other even-order terms.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The remaining (residual) terms represent the difference mentioned above and are tidal force (acceleration) terms.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] When calculated in this way for the case where ∆*r* is a distance along the axis joining the centers of *m* and *M*, ${\textstyle {\vec {a}}_{t}}$ is directed outwards from to the center of *m* (where ∆*r* is zero).
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Tidal accelerations can also be calculated away from the axis connecting the bodies *m* and *M*, requiring a vector calculation.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] In the plane perpendicular to that axis, the tidal acceleration is directed inwards (towards the center where ∆*r* is zero), and its magnitude is ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\left|{\vec {a}}_{t,{\text{axial}}}\right|}$ in linear approximation as in Figure 2.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The tidal accelerations at the surfaces of planets in the Solar System are generally very small.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] For example, the lunar tidal acceleration at the Earth's surface along the Moon–Earth axis is about 1.1×10−7 *g*, while the solar tidal acceleration at the Earth's surface along the Sun–Earth axis is about 0.52×10−7 *g*, where *g* is the gravitational acceleration at the Earth's surface.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] Hence the tide-raising force (acceleration) due to the Sun is about 45% of that due to the Moon.
[src:gravitation/tidal-force] The solar tidal acceleration at the Earth's surface was first given by Newton in the *Principia*.
